p: Among the 505 women, 50% ( N = 257) reported having genital clinical symptoms, of whom 64% ( N = 165) were positive for the tested pathogens. A high rate of U.parvum and G.vaginalis coinfection was observed ( N = 103), among which only 49% were seen as symptomatic. No significant association was however observed between the presence of studied pathogens (when detected as single or multiple infections) and the presence of any symptoms ( p = 0.330).
